To find the value of \( a \) that makes the function \( f(x) \) continuous at \( x = 2 \), we need to ensure that the left-hand limit, the right-hand limit, and the function value at \( x = 2 \) are all equal.

The function \( f(x) \) is defined as:
\[
f(x) =
\begin{cases}
2x^2 - 3 & \text{if } x \le 2, \\
ax + 4 & \text{if } x > 2.
\end{cases}
\]

First, we calculate \( f(2) \) using the first part of the function:
\[
f(2) = 2(2)^2 - 3 = 2 \cdot 4 - 3 = 8 - 3 = 5.
\]

Next, we find the right-hand limit as \( x \) approaches 2 using the second part of the function:
\[
\lim_{x \to 2^+} f(x) = a(2) + 4 = 2a + 4.
\]

For the function to be continuous at \( x = 2 \), this right-hand limit must equal \( f(2) \):
\[
2a + 4 = 5.
\]

Solving for \( a \):
\[
2a + 4 = 5 \\
2a = 1 \\
a = \frac{1}{2}.
\]

